{"title_page": "Bill Stealey", "text_new": "\n\n\n{{autobiography|date=February 2018}}\n\n\n'''John Wilbur Stealey Sr.''' is an American game developer and publisher who founded [[MicroProse]] with [[Sid Meier]]. He also founded (in 1995) and is the current [[CEO]] of [[iEntertainment Network]] <ref>[https://corporate-ient.com/about/ About iEntertainment Network]</ref>. \n\n==Business career==\nStealey took a job with [[General Instrument]] as their Director of Strategic Planning for their Systems and Service Division in Hunt Valley, Maryland.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}} There he met [[Sid Meier]] and co-founded his first game company, [[MicroProse]] Software. As CEO he grew the company to over $43 million in annual sales, taking MicroProse Software public in 1991, and selling in 1993 to a Kleiner Perkins company, [[Spectrum HoloByte]]. He resigned from the company following the merger.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=Interactive Magic |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=September 1996|pages=109\u2013110}}</ref>\n\nStealey started the game software company [[Interactive Magic]] in 1995, took it public in 1998, and sold to a private equity firm in 1999.\nWhile running iEntertainment Network, Stealey mentioned in a 1996 interview that owned his own military training aircraft and flew it for recreation on a regular basis.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=An Interview with \"Wild Bill\" Stealey |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=September 1996|page=112}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nStealey graduated from the [[United States Air Force Academy]] in 1970 and was, at the time he co-founded Microprose, a Major in the [[Air Force Reserve Command|USAF Reserve]] and instructor for the [[Pennsylvania Air National Guard]], flying [[Cessna A-37 Dragonfly|A-37]] attack aircraft.<ref>Gamers At Work: Stories Behind the Games People Play, by Morgan Ramsay, {{ISBN|1430233516}}</ref> He retired from the military with the rank of Lt Col.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/press-releases/2019-02-20/microprose-and-ientertainment-network-inc-announce-co-publishing-of-warbirds-2020-online-combat-flight-simulation MicroProse and iEntertainment Network Inc. Announce Co-Publishing of WarBirds 2020, Online Combat Flight Simulation: Bloomberg.com]</ref>\n\nStealey owned the [[Baltimore Spirit]] of the [[National Professional Soccer League (1984&ndash;2001)|National Professional Soccer League]] from the [[professional sports league organization|franchise]]'s inception in 1992 until he sold it to Edwin F. Hale, Sr. in 1998.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/stories/1997/08/11/story1.html Ey, Craig S. \"Can soccer succeed in Baltimore?\" ''Baltimore Business Journal'', Friday, August 8, 1997.]</ref><ref>[http://www.kicksfan.com/opponents/baltimore/new/index.htm Sidekicks Opponents: Baltimore Blast (new-MISL) &ndash; kicksfans.com.]</ref>\n\n''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' listed Stealey in their \"75 Most Important People in the Games Industry of 1995\" for his roles as former head of MicroProse and then-current head of Interactive Magic.<ref>{{cite journal|last= |first= |title=75 Power Players|journal=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=11|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=November 1995|page=53}}</ref> Stealey left the company in 1999, but later returned as CEO in 2002.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n[https://www.linkedin.com/in/jw-wild-bill-stealey-47b25/ LinkedIn Profile]\n* {{moby developer|id=989|name=Bill Stealey's profile}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stealey, Bill}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:American video game designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:MicroProse people]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Blast]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n\n{{autobiography|date=February 2018}}\n\n\n'''John Wilbur Stealey Sr.''' is an American game developer and publisher who founded [[MicroProse]] with [[Sid Meier]]. He also founded (in 1995) and is the current [[CEO]] of [[iEntertainment Network]] <ref>[https://corporate-ient.com/about/ About iEntertainment Network]</ref>. \n\n==Business career==\nStealey took a job with [[General Instrument]] as their Director of Strategic Planning for their Systems and Service Division in Hunt Valley, Maryland.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}} There he met [[Sid Meier]] and co-founded his first game company, [[MicroProse]] Software. As CEO he grew the company to over $43 million in annual sales, taking MicroProse Software public in 1991, and selling in 1993 to a Kleiner Perkins company, [[Spectrum HoloByte]]. He resigned from the company following the merger.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=Interactive Magic |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=September 1996|pages=109\u2013110}}</ref>\n\nStealey started the game software company [[Interactive Magic]] in 1995, took it public in 1998, and sold to a private equity firm in 1999.\nWhile running iEntertainment Network, Stealey mentioned in a 1996 interview that owned his own military training aircraft and flew it for recreation on a regular basis.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first= |title=An Interview with \"Wild Bill\" Stealey |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=September 1996|page=112}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nStealey graduated from the [[United States Air Force Academy]] in 1970 and was, at the time he co-founded Microprose, a Major in the [[Air Force Reserve Command|USAF Reserve]] and instructor for the [[Pennsylvania Air National Guard]], flying [[Cessna A-37 Dragonfly|A-37]] attack aircraft.<ref>Gamers At Work: Stories Behind the Games People Play, by Morgan Ramsay, {{ISBN|1430233516}}</ref> He retired from the military with the rank of Lt Col.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/press-releases/2019-02-20/microprose-and-ientertainment-network-inc-announce-co-publishing-of-warbirds-2020-online-combat-flight-simulation MicroProse and iEntertainment Network Inc. Announce Co-Publishing of WarBirds 2020, Online Combat Flight Simulation: Bloomberg.com]</ref>\n\nStealey owned the [[Baltimore Spirit]] of the [[National Professional Soccer League (1984&ndash;2001)|National Professional Soccer League]] from the [[professional sports league organization|franchise]]'s inception in 1992 until he sold it to Edwin F. Hale, Sr. in 1998.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/stories/1997/08/11/story1.html Ey, Craig S. \"Can soccer succeed in Baltimore?\" ''Baltimore Business Journal'', Friday, August 8, 1997.]</ref><ref>[http://www.kicksfan.com/opponents/baltimore/new/index.htm Sidekicks Opponents: Baltimore Blast (new-MISL) &ndash; kicksfans.com.]</ref>\n\n''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' listed Stealey in their \"75 Most Important People in the Games Industry of 1995\" for his roles as former head of MicroProse and then-current head of Interactive Magic.<ref>{{cite journal|last= |first= |title=75 Power Players|journal=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=11|publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=November 1995|page=53}}</ref> Stealey left the company in 1999, but later returned as CEO in 2002.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n[https://www.linkedin.com/in/jw-wild-bill-stealey-47b25/ LinkedIn Profile]\n* {{moby developer|id=989|name=Bill Stealey's profile}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stealey, Bill}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:American video game designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:MicroProse]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Blast]]\n", "name_user": "Mika1h", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_Stealey"}
